<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBFFFE56FAFFB2DFC23AE24" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBFFFE56FAFFB2DFC23AE24" blockId="27.[178,1086,1121,1318]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBFFFE56E35FB2DFC2EAFC7" authorityName="CHEVROLAT. Part" authorityYear="1834" box="[837,955,1200,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Platynoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBFFFE56E35FB2DFC2EAFC7" box="[837,955,1200,1221]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">Platynoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as defined in 
<bibRefCitation id="305471FAFFBFFFE56D97FB54FE46AFDD" author="CORPORAAL J" box="[231,467,1224,1247]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540" refId="ref25941" refString="CORPORAAL J. B. (1950): Cleridae. - In: HINCKS W. D. (ed.), Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa, Pars 23 (editio secunda). W. Junk's: ' s-Gravenhage, Netherlands, 373 pp." type="book" year="1950">CORPORAAL (1950: 273)</bibRefCitation>
, contains several non-congeneric species and it is not possible to determine which references listed by Corporaal refer to 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBFFFE56E6CFB7DFC07AFF7" authorityName="CHEVROLAT. Part" authorityYear="1834" box="[796,914,1248,1269]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Platynoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBFFFE56E6CFB7DFC07AFF7" box="[796,914,1248,1269]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">Platynoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as now defined. Moreover, several species have been misidentified. Therefore, the reader should note that generic references listed by Corporaal may not refer to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBFFFE56E4AFA8DFC25AE27" authorityName="CHEVROLAT. Part" authorityYear="1834" box="[826,944,1296,1317]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Platynoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBFFFE56E4AFA8DFC25AE27" box="[826,944,1296,1317]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">Platynoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBFFFE56DC2FAAAFCB3AE68" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540" type="description">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBFFFE56DC2FAAAFCB3AE68" blockId="27.[178,1085,1335,1386]" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">
Diagnosis: Within 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBFFFE56CB9FAAAFDFDAE4F" box="[457,616,1335,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Platynopterinae">Platynopterinae</taxonomicName>
only the members of 
<taxonomicName id="93C57788FFBFFFE56E26FAAAFC4FAE4E" authorityName="CHEVROLAT. Part" authorityYear="1834" box="[854,986,1335,1356]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Platynoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBFFFE56E26FAAAFC4FAE4E" box="[854,986,1335,1356]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">Platynoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the maxillary and labial terminal palpomeres strongly securiform.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBFFFE26DC2FAE4FD43A8D2" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="1541" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540" type="description">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBFFFE26DC2FAE4FD43A8D2" blockId="27.[178,1085,1401,1593]" lastBlockId="28.[178,1086,218,976]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="1541" pageId="27" pageNumber="1540">
Description: Size: Length 10.0-18.0 mm; width 4.5-10.0. Form: Elytra trapezoidal, posterior angle broadly rounded. Integumental color: Antenna always black; mouthparts unicolorous or bicolorous, when bicolorous terminal palpomeres black, other portions flavotestaceous, when unicolorous, flavotestaceous or black; cranium mostly black, epicranium and gular region may be flavotestaceous; pronotum bicolorous, flavotestaceous at upper sides and black at lower sides, disc may show broad black macula, or two black lines; elytra mostly black with flavotestaceous markings, rarely all flavotestaceous or all black; legs black; pterothorax and abdomen black. Vestiture: Integument highly setose, funicular antennomeres densely setose, cranium and pronotum densely vested with decumbent setae, elytra densely vested with short 2° setae and fewer 1° setae that become more prominent along epipleural and sutural margins; legs highly setose. Head (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26D86FED6FEFBAA62" box="[246,366,331,353]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Figs. 32-34</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26C09FED6FE03AA63" box="[377,406,331,353]" captionStart="Figs 97-102" captionStartId="32.[178,218,1198,1220]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,219,1180]" captionTargetId="figure-170@32.[178,1085,219,1188]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 97-102: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (97) Head, frontal view; (98) Protibia; (99) Metathoracic leg; (100) Male metathoracic leg showing glandular pit; (101) Metatibial tarsus; (102) Pronotal disc showing incipient trichobothrium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294874/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">97</figureCitation>
): Cranial setose punctation small; eyes bulging, finely faceted and deeply broadly incised along frontal margin; antenna (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26F93FEF5FCB8AA7C" box="[739,813,360,382]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
) capitate, inserted at level of eye incision (= ocular notch); antennal carina very prominent, comprised of 11 antennomeres, scape very robust, pedicel triangular, funicular antennomeres transverse, capitulum very long, about three times longer that length of other antennomeres combined, antennomeres 9 and 10 rectangulate; labrum (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26FD0FE44FD65AAED" box="[672,752,473,495]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
) not deeply incised, transverse tormal process horizontal and contiguous; mandible (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26FABFE68FCB2A909" box="[731,807,501,523]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) robust, dens well developed, penicillus reduced; maxilla (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26F7FFD8CFDC9A925" box="[527,604,529,551]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
) well developed, terminal palpomere strongly securiform, laterolacinia present; labium (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26F18FDB3FD20A946" box="[616,693,558,580]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) well developed, terminal palpomere strongly securiform; gula (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26CB7FDD7FD86A962" box="[455,531,586,608]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) broadly triangular. Thorax (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26E34FDD7FC50A962" box="[836,965,586,608]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Figs. 37, 38</figureCitation>
): Pronotum with incipient trichobothrium (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26C84FDFBFDC5A97F" box="[500,592,614,637]" captionStart="Figs 97-102" captionStartId="32.[178,218,1198,1220]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,219,1180]" captionTargetId="figure-170@32.[178,1085,219,1188]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 97-102: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (97) Head, frontal view; (98) Protibia; (99) Metathoracic leg; (100) Male metathoracic leg showing glandular pit; (101) Metatibial tarsus; (102) Pronotal disc showing incipient trichobothrium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294874/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 102</figureCitation>
), usually elongate, rarely quadrate, indented at sides or not, side margins with shallow tubercle, anterior margin projecting at middle or not, prebasal depression feebly developed, dorsolateral carina not extended to anterior margin of pronotum, carina joins pronotal hem at pronotal posterior angle; elytra trapezoidal, increasingly widened to rounded posterior angles, with discal carinae; mesoscutellum subglobose; protibial anterior margin spinous (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26FA4FD69FCB5A808" box="[724,800,756,778]" captionStart="Figs 97-102" captionStartId="32.[178,218,1198,1220]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,219,1180]" captionTargetId="figure-170@32.[178,1085,219,1188]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 97-102: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (97) Head, frontal view; (98) Protibia; (99) Metathoracic leg; (100) Male metathoracic leg showing glandular pit; (101) Metatibial tarsus; (102) Pronotal disc showing incipient trichobothrium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294874/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
); ungues with denticle (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26964FD69FF4EA824" captionStart="Figs 97-102" captionStartId="32.[178,218,1198,1220]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,219,1180]" captionTargetId="figure-170@32.[178,1085,219,1188]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 97-102: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (97) Head, frontal view; (98) Protibia; (99) Metathoracic leg; (100) Male metathoracic leg showing glandular pit; (101) Metatibial tarsus; (102) Pronotal disc showing incipient trichobothrium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294874/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
); tibial spur formula 0-1-1; tarsal pulvillar formula 3-3-3; metathoracic wing as in 
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26DC2FCB0FE95A840" box="[178,256,812,835]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
; metendosternite (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26CB2FCB0FD85A841" box="[450,528,813,835]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) with furcal lamina; glandular pit on male metatibia (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26DCAFCD4FED1A85D" box="[186,324,841,863]" captionStart="Figs 97-102" captionStartId="32.[178,218,1198,1220]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,219,1180]" captionTargetId="figure-170@32.[178,1085,219,1188]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figs 97-102: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (97) Head, frontal view; (98) Protibia; (99) Metathoracic leg; (100) Male metathoracic leg showing glandular pit; (101) Metatibial tarsus; (102) Pronotal disc showing incipient trichobothrium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5294874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5294874/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Figs. 99, 100</figureCitation>
). Abdomen: Six visible sternites; pygidium rounded distally in both sexes. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26C21FCF8FE5BA879" box="[337,462,869,891]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Figs. 41, 43</figureCitation>
): Aedeagus short, tegmen slightly sclerotized, lobate distally, fimbriate, phallus well sclerotized; spicular fork (
<figureCitation id="CCFE108EFFB8FFE26FBAFC1FFC8FA89A" box="[714,794,898,920]" captionStart="Figs 31-45" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1294,1316]" captionTargetBox="[198,1079,259,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1085,228,1276]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31-45: Morphological organs of Platynoptera lyciformis. (31) Antenna, male; (32) Head, frontal view; (33) Head, ventral view; (34) Head, dorsal view; (35) Mandible; (36) Maxilla; (37) Pronotum, ventral view; (38) Pronotum, dorsal view; (39) Labium; (40) Metendosternite; 41) Phallus; (42) Spicular fork; (43) Tegmen; (44) Labrum; (45) Metathoracic wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5282509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5282509/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
) comprised of two narrow plates that do not connect distally, intraspicular plate narrow and long. Female genitalia: Ovipositor short; dorsal and ventral laminae unilobed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFB8FFE26DC2FC42FC77A8F7" box="[178,994,991,1013]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541" type="description">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFB8FFE26DC2FC42FC77A8F7" blockId="28.[178,994,991,1013]" box="[178,994,991,1013]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">
Distribution: The members of this genus range from 
<collectingCountry id="2CD24C9BFFB8FFE26E40FC42FCE8A8F7" box="[816,893,991,1013]" name="Mexico" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">México</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="2CD24C9BFFB8FFE26EEDFC42FC4BA8F7" box="[925,990,991,1013]" name="Brazil" pageId="28" pageNumber="1541">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
